<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-12-23T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-12-23T05:00:00-05:00" n="446" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d446">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/13827: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-12-23T18:00:00+08:00">December 23, 1936—6
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 23—11:18 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>377. British Ambassador, who has just seen Kung, reports Kung as stating
                            that there will be no developments within next 2 or 3 days but hopeful
                            that private negotiations’ now proceeding will result <pb facs="0542" n="447" xml:id="pg_447"/> in something by that time. Military
                            operations have been suspended pending result.</p>
                        <p>Sent to the Department, code text by mail to Peiping, Tokyo.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>